  <h1>TDS on property purchase under Section 194IA</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>5 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>Section 194IA requires the buyer of immovable property (other than agricultural land) to deduct TDS at 1% where the consideration or the stamp-duty value is Rs.50 lakh or more.</b> The buyer pays it using Form 26QB within 30 days, without needing a TAN.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">The rule</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">Joint buyers and sellers</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">Process</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Common errors</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">The rule</h2>
<p>On purchase of immovable property (land or building, other than rural agricultural land) where the <b>consideration or stamp-duty value is Rs.50 lakh or more</b>, the buyer deducts <b>1%</b> TDS on the higher of the two values, at the time of payment or credit. No TAN is required; the buyer uses <b>Form 26QB</b> (a challan-cum-statement) and issues <b>Form 16B</b> to the seller.</p>

  <h2 id="s1">Joint buyers and sellers</h2>
<p>Where there are multiple buyers or sellers, the Rs.50 lakh threshold is judged on the <b>total consideration of the property</b>, not each person's share. Each buyer files a 26QB for their portion. For a <b>non-resident seller</b>, TDS is governed by <a href="tds-foreign-payments-section-195-dtaa.html">Section 195</a> (not 194IA), usually at a higher rate.</p>

  <h2 id="s2">Process</h2>
<ol><li>Deduct 1% at each payment/instalment.</li><li>File Form 26QB within <b>30 days</b> of the end of the month of deduction.</li><li>Download Form 16B and give it to the seller.</li><li>Ensure the seller's PAN is correct (else 20% under 206AA).</li></ol>

  <h2 id="s3">Common errors</h2>
<ul><li>Not deducting because each instalment is below Rs.50 lakh &mdash; the threshold is the property value, not the instalment.</li><li>Deducting 1% when the seller is a non-resident &mdash; that case is Section 195.</li><li>Missing the stamp-value comparison.</li><li>Late 26QB &mdash; attracts 234E fee and 201(1A) interest.</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>When is TDS deducted on buying property?</summary><p>When the consideration or stamp-duty value of the immovable property (other than rural agricultural land) is Rs.50 lakh or more; the buyer deducts 1% under Section 194IA.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Do I need a TAN for 194IA TDS?</summary><p>No. The buyer uses Form 26QB, a challan-cum-statement, and does not need a TAN; Form 16B is then issued to the seller.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What if the seller is a non-resident?</summary><p>Section 194IA does not apply; TDS is governed by Section 195, generally at a higher rate based on the capital gains, with treaty relief where applicable.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>194IA: 1% TDS on property of Rs.50 lakh or more.</li><li>Threshold is the property value, not the instalment.</li><li>Pay via Form 26QB within 30 days; no TAN needed.</li><li>Non-resident seller: use Section 195, not 194IA.</li></ul>
  </div>

